### *An Iatrogenic Imperative: Weight-Goal Pursuit and Morbidity from Adolescence to Adulthood*

Since the mid-twentieth century, American medicine and public health have been organized around the weight-centered health paradigm — the conviction that 'excess' weight is dangerous for health and that its reduction will produce healthier populations. This dissertation inverts the paradigm's central assumption: rather than asking what a larger body does to health, it asks what the sustained pursuit of a smaller one does. Drawing on five waves of the National Longitudinal Study of Adolescent to Adult Health (Add Health), I operationalize this pursuit as membership in distinct weight-goal trajectories traced from adolescence into adulthood and follow it across three linked studies. The first asks who the paradigm recruits into weight-goal pursuit and finds that recruitment is near-total and socially structured: fewer than one in twenty adolescents held no weight goal, women were sorted overwhelmingly toward loss and men toward gain, and perceived weight status predicted sustained loss pursuit far more powerfully than clinical BMI classification. The second asks what the pursuit does, and finds that trajectory membership is the dominant predictor of goal-directed weight-control behavior, with sustained loss pursuit roughly two and a half times as likely to involve extreme practices and dieting specifically predicting escalation into them. The third asks what the pursuit leaves behind, and finds that sustained pursuit and the behaviors it motivates predict elevated cardiometabolic and mental-health morbidity into the thirties and forties — associations only partially attenuated by body size. Together the studies identify the paradigm as iatrogenic in the strict sense: a harm produced by the intervention meant to prevent it, pressed most insistently on those already marked as falling short of an approved body, and returned to the paradigm as apparent vindication. A substantial share of the ill health attributed to fat bodies is, on this evidence, the ill health of the campaign waged against them.

